cs.SI, cs.SOC, cs.IT, cs.DS, cs.CE 

The paper deals with the issue of information asymmetry in socio-economic networks, which involves the analysis of network structures and the quantification of relevant systemic properties. This suggests that the paper could belong to several arXiv CS sub-categories, including cs.SI (Social and Information Networks), cs.SOC (Computational Social Science), cs.IT (Information Theory), cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms), and cs.CE (Computational Engineering, Finance, and Science). Among these, cs.SI and cs.SOC are the most likely categories, as they are directly related to the study of social and economic networks. The use of entropy-maximization techniques also suggests a possible connection to cs.IT, while the focus on ranking nodes according to their information content could be relevant to cs.DS and cs.CE.
